From: ms178 <ms178@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Sun, 20 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] ssl_gtest: fix static-initialization-order fiasco in
 tls_subcerts (delegated-credential nickname globals)

The four namespace-scope globals in tls_subcerts_unittest.cc are
dynamically initialized by *copying* std::string objects that are
defined in a different translation unit (tls_agent.cc):

    const std::string kEcdsaDelegatorId = TlsAgent::kDelegatorEcdsa256;
    const std::string kRsaeDelegatorId  = TlsAgent::kDelegatorRsae2048;
    const std::string kPssDelegatorId   = TlsAgent::kDelegatorRsaPss2048;
    const std::string kDCId             = TlsAgent::kServerEcdsa256;

The relative order of dynamic initialization of non-local objects with
static storage duration defined in different translation units is
unspecified ([basic.start.dynamic]). In a non-LTO build the object-file
link order happens to construct tls_agent.cc's statics before this file's
copies, so the copies observe fully-constructed source strings. Under LTO
(GCC -flto=auto, or Clang ThinLTO) the whole program is merged into a
single unit and the toolchain is free to schedule this file's global
constructors *before* tls_agent.cc's, so the copies are constructed from
still-zero-initialized (empty) std::string sources.

The consequence is a silent, hard-to-diagnose failure that is NOT a
codegen bug: every one of these four ids ends up as the empty string.
PK11_FindCertFromNickname() is then called with an empty CKA_LABEL,
finds no certificate and returns NULL. The Delegated-Credential tests
(DCDelegation.DCDelegations, TlsConnectTls13.DCNotConfigured, and the
DCConnect* family) wrap LoadCertificate() in EXPECT_* (not ASSERT_*), so
execution continues with a NULL certificate and the process then crashes
with SIGSEGV inside SSL_DelegateCredential(). During a profile-guided
optimization run this aborts the whole test/training pass.

Fix: bind these ids as references to the canonical TlsAgent members
instead of copying them. A reference to another object with static
storage duration is a constant initialization performed at load time, so
it introduces no global constructor and no initialization-order
dependency whatsoever -- the SIOF is eliminated by construction rather
than merely hidden by link order. All downstream uses already take
`const std::string&`, so this is source-compatible and behaviourally
identical to a correctly-ordered build.

This makes the ssl_gtest suite pass reliably under LTO with both GCC and
Clang toolchains.
---
 gtests/ssl_gtest/tls_subcerts_unittest.cc | 8 ++++----
 1 file changed, 4 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/gtests/ssl_gtest/tls_subcerts_unittest.cc b/gtests/ssl_gtest/tls_subcerts_unittest.cc
--- a/gtests/ssl_gtest/tls_subcerts_unittest.cc
+++ b/gtests/ssl_gtest/tls_subcerts_unittest.cc
@@ -18,10 +18,10 @@
 
 namespace nss_test {
 
-const std::string kEcdsaDelegatorId = TlsAgent::kDelegatorEcdsa256;
-const std::string kRsaeDelegatorId = TlsAgent::kDelegatorRsae2048;
-const std::string kPssDelegatorId = TlsAgent::kDelegatorRsaPss2048;
-const std::string kDCId = TlsAgent::kServerEcdsa256;
+const std::string& kEcdsaDelegatorId = TlsAgent::kDelegatorEcdsa256;
+const std::string& kRsaeDelegatorId = TlsAgent::kDelegatorRsae2048;
+const std::string& kPssDelegatorId = TlsAgent::kDelegatorRsaPss2048;
+const std::string& kDCId = TlsAgent::kServerEcdsa256;
 const SSLSignatureScheme kDCScheme = ssl_sig_ecdsa_secp256r1_sha256;
 const PRUint32 kDCValidFor = 60 * 60 * 24 * 7 /* 1 week (seconds) */;
 
